title: Trump Supporters, Proud Boys March To US Capitol On 5th Anniversary Of January 6 Attacks | 10 News
description: Trump supporters, including far-right group the Proud Boys, marched towards the US Capitol on the fifth anniversary of the January 6 attacks. The rally was organised by Enrique Tarrio, a former Proud Boys leader recently pardoned by Trump after serving time for his role in the attack. Tarrio is one of over 1,500 people whose charges were dropped after Trump issued sweeping pardons last year. Micki Witthoeft, mother of Ashli Babbitt, a Trump supporter killed at the Capitol in 2021, joined the march, saying she was proud to be Babbitt’s mother and calling for the release of January 6 defendant Tina Peters. Counterprotesters gathered nearby, but a strong police presence kept the two groups apart.

title: Donald Trump Threatens Greenland, Car Theft Syndicate Busted, Cortnee Vine Interview | 10 News+
description: Marco Rubio, the US Secretary of State, says President Donald Trump wants to ‘buy’ the territory of Greenland. The White House has also insisted military action is not off the table. Greenland, the world’s largest island, is strategically important because it sits on a pivotal maritime passage, along with Iceland and the UK, that links the Arctic to the North Atlantic. It’s also rich in natural resources including oil, gas and rare earth minerals, which can be used to manufacture everything from electric cars to military equipment.  Cortnee Vine is known as the Matildas’ match-winner and the golden girl who led Australia to a World Cup semi-final on home soil. In the past two years, she has been forced to step away from soccer to tackle her anxiety. Sitting down with Tara Rushton for 10 News+, the star striker opens up about her mental health battle, and explains why she is ready to return to the sport and represent her country once again.  Seven men have been arrested in Queensland during overnight raids, accused of being part of an international syndicate that was behind the thefts of $9 million worth of cars. Authorities say the men used high-tech tools to steal around 60 SUVs from suburban driveways between October and December 2025, which were then allegedly hidden in shipping containers and sent to the United Arab Emirates for sale.
